Argia vivida is a species of damselfly that belongs to the family Coenagrionidae. 
The body of Argia vivida is relatively small, ranging from 25-34 mm in length. 
Males of the species are usually bright blue or greenish-blue in color, while females have more muted colors of green or brown. 
The wings of Argia vivida are transparent and have a wingspan of around 34-38 mm. 
This species is commonly found in North American freshwater habitats, particularly near rivers or streams. 
Argia vivida is known to skim the surface of the water and perch on vegetation or rocks. 
The bright colors and delicate appearance of Argia vivida make it a popular subject for photography and observation in nature.
